rom the hamstring tendons or patellar tendon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERehabilitation is extensive and prolonged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ligaments is most likely being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior cruciate ligament","Lateral collateral ligament","Medial collateral ligament","Patellar ligament","Posterior cruciate ligament"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior cruciate ligament\u003C/strong\u003E (ACL) is the ligament being described. It is a crucial stabiliser of the knee joint and does not heal well on its own after rupture. Treatment often involves reconstruction using grafts from the hamstring tendons or patellar tendon, followed by an extensive rehabilitation program.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament can often heal with conservative treatment and does not typically require reconstruction.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - Similar to the medial collateral ligament, it can often heal without surgical intervention.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior cruciate ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament can sometimes heal with conservative management and does not always require reconstruction.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatellar ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not typically reconstructed in the same manner as the ACL, as it is used as a graft source for ACL reconstruction.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) is a key stabiliser of the knee joint and does not heal well on its own after rupture.","ACL reconstruction often involves 